      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Waco's Ashes, A Burden of Guilt</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lopis Erwin letter comments on July 25 editorial on report by former Sen John Danforth exonerating Atty Gen Janet Reno and federal government from guilt in raid by federal agents on Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Tex</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Danforth's Verdict on Waco'' (editorial, July 25):</p>
        <p>John C. Danforth's report exonerates Attorney General Janet Reno and the government from guilt in the Waco tragedy in 1993 and firmly places blame for the deaths on the leader of the Branch Davidians, David Koresh.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Danforth's Verdict on Waco'' (editorial, July 25):</p>
        <p>John C. Danforth's report exonerates Attorney General Janet Reno and the government from guilt in the Waco tragedy in 1993 and firmly places blame for the deaths on the leader of the Branch Davidians, David Koresh.</p>
        <p>But will those who accused the government of murder at Waco now retract those allegations, or will they continue to chant ''Remember Waco''?</p>
        <p>While remaining vigilant about our government's actions, it is time for the rest of us to ''remember Waco'' by paying heed to Mr. Danforth's admonition that we be skeptical of ''sensational accusations'' of government evil.</p>
        <p>LOIS ERWIN  Waldwick, N.J., July 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
